subsection.p:
In (a), we have a sphere of radius R that is uniformly charged with constant value of \rho_0 everywhere. Therefore, its charge density can be written as a piecewise function of r only, being same in all directions.

	\rho(r,\theta, \phi) = \begin{cases}
			\rho_0 \amp 0\le r \le R\\
			0 \amp r \gt R.
			\end{cases}

 			Consider a uniformly charged sphere with charge density

 				\rho = \begin{cases}
			 			\rho_0 \amp 0\le r \le R\\
			 			0 \amp r \gt R.
			 			\end{cases}

 			We will show below that the magnitude of electric field varies with distance by two different rules, one for points inside the sphere and another for point outside the sphere.

 				E = \begin{cases}
			 			 \dfrac{\rho_0}{3\epsilon_0}\, r \amp  0\le r \le R,\\
			 			\dfrac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\, \dfrac{q_\text{tot}}{r^2} \amp r \gt R,
			 			\end{cases}

 			where q_\text{tot} is the total charge on the sphere.  shows a drawing of this function.

solution.p:
(c)	The flux will be given by Gauss's law.  All charges in the sphere are enclosed by the surface at 4 cm radius.

	 \Phi \amp = \frac{q_{\text{enc}}}{\epsilon_0} 
	 \amp = \frac{2.26\times 10^{-13}\:\text{C}}{8.85\times10^{-12}\:\text{C}^2/\text{N.m}^2}
	 \amp = 2.56\times 10^{-2}\: \text{N.m}^2/\text{C}.


(d)	Here only the charges inside the 2-cm radius from the center of the sphere matters.  Hence,

	 \Phi \amp = \frac{q_{\text{enc}}}{\epsilon_0} 
	 \amp = \frac{6.70\times 10^{-14}\:\text{C}}{8.85\times10^{-12}\:\text{C}^2/\text{N.m}^2} 
	 \amp = 7.57\times 10^{-3}\: \text{N.m}^2/\text{C}
